Bombarding in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the president's main strengths, American Barack Obama.
It seems that his words have ultimately led him into a trap today.
After saying in March last year that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning a "red line" that should not be crossed last year, Obama will lose face if he does not react energetically to the killing, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians by sarin gas.
Clearly, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself into this trap with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line ?
The U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry is right to describe the use of gas as "a moral obscenity".
But torturing children, a harbinger of the civil war two years ago, is equally so.
And is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemicals than to bomb them, shoot at them or let them starve to death ?
It is commonly acknowledged, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Massive destructive weapons, nuclear bombs in particular, certainly cause more and greater damage more quickly than conventional arms.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A view, advocated by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, is that swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up using chemical weapons and return to "more mundane means of massacring his people."
In my view, it makes no sense.
The question is surely one of massacre, not the methods used.
In any case, moral indignation, as justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is it therefore a question of law? The use of chemical weapons is in fact a violation of international conventions, including the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, which Syria has never signed and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, incidentally, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a policy easily defendable.
The Western community, or Western countries, or the United States as the principal Western power, should presumably draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent civilians are being massacred on a large scale ?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should a line be drawn ?
How many murders constitute a genocide ?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Does the number not come into play?
A genocide, after all, is a matter of intent, involving a will to kill or persecute individuals due to their race, ethnic background, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for those reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The question can be approached from a different perspective.
The question to consider before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
To determine the best course of action.
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
As the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" has more chances of producing a result in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would contemplate missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or enforcing international norms and conventions governing war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not a major power either.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more significant countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
It is beyond doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It's not at all clear that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a wider conflict.
In fact, some proponents of an American intervention – both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks" – seem to want the opposite: they are calling for a war with Iran.
And Obama probably drew a connection in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he had drawn for Iran, perhaps in an equally unreflective manner, to prevent it from developing a nuclear weapon.
What, then, can we expect from U.S. strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they were not intended to topple the Syrian regime ?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile will make the United States a direct participant in this war, sparking a surge in violence.
Taking that risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly wise.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including some rebels.
It is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of most Americans.
It's perhaps even Obama's opinion, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the US Congress the authorization to use force in Syria.
Since his inauguration, his relations with Congress have been far from smooth.
But he needs it more than ever now to cover his tracks.
